At 6:00 p.m., about ten hours after Early had displaced Gibbon and retaken Marye's Heights, Anderson and McLaws were finally in place for attack on the Confederate left. Throughout the course of the day, as Lee struggled to wrangle his army into position for attack, Sedgwick realized that he was surrounded on three sides by the Confederate army and had become increasingly worried about his ability to repel the inevitable attack and hold the position south of the Rappahannock. Sedgwick sent repeated messages to Hooker in Chancellorsville asking for support, but Sedgwick refused to send reinforcements.<div><br></div><div>The Confederate attack started about an hour before nightfall. The first charges were successful, but the assault became confused and scattered on the right side as darkness fell and the divisions led by Anderson and McLaws started colliding with one another as they pushed eastward into the Union defenses below the river. Lee sent messages to the left instructing McLaws to continue the assault at all costs, warning that a premature end to the attack would give Sedgwick time to regroup and force the Confederates to fight the same battle for a second time in the morning.</div><div><br></div><div>McLaws and Anderson persisted, and forced Sedgwick's line back around the two pontoon bridges leading back across the river. Sedgwick sent messages to Hooker at about 11:00 p.m. asking for permission to retreat. Hooker issued the order, before reversing his decision a few minutes later. Sedgwick started moving troops across the Rappahannock on receiving the first order, though, and continued to do so throughout the early hours of the next day.</div><div><br></div><div>_______________________</div><div><br></div>


